Summary: Explains how GDScript handles references and memory management compared to C++ and Java.
In GDScript, only base types (int, float, string, and vector types) are passed by value to functions, meaning a copy of the value is made. All other data types, including instances, arrays, and dictionaries, are passed by reference. Classes that inherit from RefCounted (the default behavior) are automatically freed when they are no longer in use. Manual memory management is also possible if a class inherits directly from Object.

GDScript's approach to references is similar to Java, where objects are treated as references and managed by a garbage collector. This contrasts with C++, which requires manual memory management using `new` and `delete` to avoid memory leaks.

GDScript:
```gdscript
func use_class(instance): # Does not care about class type
    instance.use() # Will work with any class that has a ".use()" method.

func do_something():
    var instance = SomeClass.new() # Created as reference.
    use_class(instance) # Passed as reference.
    # Will be unreferenced and deleted.
```
---CHUNK---
